<p>Hello Granite Mask! let's take a look :)</p>
<p><strong>SAND</strong></p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>The concept:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Elevator Pitch: The Laughing Tree is a memetic entity rooted within an old wooden-tent campground commonly used by scouts or youth groups. The tree convinces children to tie one of their own to its trunk, and, when secured, it carves their name into its bark. These victims live on to help the tree find new prey, and laugh at the pain and suffering it inflicts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Overall the premise sounds interesting, however, theres a few things that don't really add up to me (or aren't really explained/clarified). They're as follows;</p>
<p>-how exactly does the tree convince you to tie someone up?<br />
-does the tree itself carve the child's name? or do the children do it?<br />
-how exactly do these victims live on to help the tree? do they still have any free will? what happens when they leave the camp?<br />
-what exactly happens <em>after</em> ones name is carved?- in the immediate future?</p>
<p><strong>The narratives:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Central Narrative: A low-level foundation member calls attention to this entity after his child is almost tied to the tree. Previously, he laughed the tale off as a &quot;camp story&quot; to several co-workers. He is told to bring in his child for questioning.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This makes me a bit skeptical, the Foundation doesn't really have any real reason to believe this is an anomaly. Especially considering they how little context they have.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The first interiew is short. After providing a cover story, the investigator asks what happened. Emotionally dead, the kid replies, &quot;you'll just laugh at me..&quot;</p>
<p>The second interview occurs after the parent tries to console their child. The parent tries to help answer preliminary questions by describing camp activities. At the mention of knot-tying, the child's face goes pale.</p>
<p>The interviewer asks why the child didn't want to attend camp. Instead of answering he makes a small digression about how he felt sorry for a spider that another kid burned. The parent interrupts and describes his child as socially isolated and wonders if this behavior is related to the nature of his work.<br />
Eventually, the child describes what happened, One-by-one belongings of other scouts find their way to his tent. Camp staff approach him and ask about thefts. The child tries to explain that he didn't take them, but they laugh at him. He runs. Then they, the scouts, surround him with knot-tying ropes and force him toward the *tree*. He tries and fails to escape, as the scouts laugh at him. The laughter grows louder.. and deeper until he realizes that it's coming from behind. And then, the laughter stops.<br />
The investigator asks what changed. The child looks down, and cries.</p>
<p>A third interview takes place with a camp staff-member and former victim. He laughs at suffering he causes, and his own.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>As it stands, it feels like I'm missing a fair amount of context here? there isn't really much of an answer to how/why the child didn't want to go to camp (were they aware something was wrong beforehand?), how/why items kept making their way to his tent (was this planned?), and what exactly happened after he got tied to the tree.- the narrative seems to imply his name got carved, but then there are also parts of the narrative that show the parent stepped in?</p>
<p><strong>Red or green?</strong><br />
Due to my afore mentioned concerns, no-greenlight</p>
