			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865666">
									

<p>Hi Sonderance, thanks for the feedback!</p>
<p>So address your points in order of easiest to hardest.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Number of testing logs</span><br />
This in and of itself is fine. I have written 9 so far, and my strength will be writing the procedural logs themselves, so this is less a concern for me. The justification for them (covered below) is trickier.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Description</span><br />
My WIP photoshopped image is here <a href="https://i.imgur.com/amUpFVk.png">https://i.imgur.com/amUpFVk.png</a>. The shortened object description is essentially a 5.5in wide stone disk with engravings suggesting non-human origin and the symbols are meant to be a form of &quot;universal&quot; description of the object.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Origin of objects</span><br />
My solution to this is that all the objects created are all &quot;specific&quot; to people/lifeforms and occasionally, the objects will be from different time periods (suggesting they were taken from someone who used it long ago). So no furniture, food, vehicles etc, and items more like clothing, immediate possessions, intimate things like memories/beliefs etc. For example one testing log will have an office briefcase containing secret documents from 50 years ago (something more likely to have disappeared/reappeared than created from thin air). Also toying with the idea of entire identities being taken/returned. I also want to keep purpose of the SCP somewhat mysterious, but it would basically be a semi-sentient &quot;collector&quot;.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Testing justification</span><br />
This is tricky, and something I haven't given an enormous amount of thought (so your feedback is very helpful :) ). My process for the logs so far is that early testing is only dangerous to the tester (creating/removing limbs etc) therefore continued testing is easier to justify as it mostly just maims/kills D class at worst. A possible solution is for the SCP to require periodic exchanges and with them, it compels people to use it (therefore necessitating testing). This fits with my purpose/origin idea but is definitely a bit of a cop out. I can think on this more.</p>

							</div>

								
					
